items.name: John Harris Style
items.description:
John Harris is a British artist known for his stunning and imaginative science fiction and fantasy artwork.

His style can be described as atmospheric and epic, often featuring vast alien landscapes, futuristic cities, and fantastical scenes.

Harris's paintings are characterized by his masterful use of color and light, creating a sense of depth and immersion in his otherworldly settings.

His attention to detail and ability to capture the essence of his subjects bring a sense of realism and believability to his artwork.

Harris's paintings evoke a sense of wonder and exploration, transporting viewers to distant galaxies and realms of imagination.

His work has been featured in science fiction books, magazines, and exhibitions, captivating audiences with its sense of awe and adventure.

John Harris's art continues to inspire and transport viewers to new and exciting worlds beyond our own.

items.name: John James Audubon Style
items.description:
John James Audubon was an American ornithologist, naturalist, and painter best known for his groundbreaking work, "The Birds of America."

His style can be described as highly detailed and realistic, showcasing his meticulous observation and scientific accuracy.

Audubon's illustrations were created using a combination of watercolor, ink, and pastels, and they depicted birds and other wildlife in their natural habitats.

His attention to detail and his ability to capture the beauty and essence of each species made his artwork both scientifically valuable and aesthetically pleasing.

"The Birds of America" consisted of life-size prints of 435 different species, making it a monumental achievement in the field of natural history illustration.

Audubon's passion for studying and documenting birds greatly contributed to our understanding of North American avian species.

His legacy as an artist and naturalist endures, and his artwork continues to inspire and educate people about the beauty and diversity of the natural world.

items.name: John Kenn Mortensen Style
items.description:
John Kenn Mortensen, also known as John Kenn, is a Danish artist and author recognized for his unique style of artwork known as "Post-it Note art" or "Monsterdoodles".

His style can be described as darkly whimsical and imaginative, often featuring detailed and expressive pen and ink drawings on yellow Post-it Notes.

Mortensen's illustrations predominantly depict creepy and surreal scenes, filled with eccentric monsters, eerie landscapes, and macabre narratives.

His artwork exudes a sense of playfulness combined with a touch of melancholy, creating a captivating juxtaposition of emotions.

Mortensen's drawings often explore themes of childhood, fear, and the intersection between reality and fantasy.

His distinctive artistic approach and the limited space of the Post-it Notes contribute to the charm and intimacy of his creations.

John Kenn Mortensen's artwork has gained a dedicated following and has been showcased in exhibitions and published in books, inviting viewers into a wonderfully strange and captivating world.

items.name: Gnarlysick - negative embedding
items.description:
Oh look, another negative embedding. This one isn't anything amazing, just something I made for personal use and figured I would share.

So what does it do? Make the colours more bold, sharpen the image a little, and make the composition/details more cohesive. It doesn't necessarily add more detail, as it may even remove some to try and make the composition cleaner / more aesthetically pleasing. It will also try to make creatures/animals more natural looking (sorta).

Oh well, give it a try. If you like it, cool, hope it helps. If not, meh- no skin off my back. loll
Sample grids are made with various random models, same seed showing with and without the embed as the only negative. No highres-fix, no facefix, no touchups, just so you can see the negative effects better.

modelVersions.description: Put in the negative tags, unless you like destroying things.

items.name: Misusing PowerPoint as OpenPose Editor
items.description:
Yes we can use a slide in PowerPoint as OpenPose editor. The benefit is not only that we don't need to go online or install an extension, but that PowerPoint doesn't restrict any proportion composition. So, with help of PowerPoint it is for us possible to

  • generate skeleton with non-standard proportion like in gorilla, chimpanzee, or orangutan;

  • copy particular limbs to make monster with 4 arms, or 2 heads;

  • or even remove a limb to draw a mermaid for instance.

Furthermore, we can insert hand keynotes and/or face keynotes, and even edit it. Those are basically just colorful circles, lines, or shapes which can be drawn and modified easily in PowerPoint.

We can also add depthmap of hand poses to our skeleton. We will also find out that lineart of hand poses might be a cleverer alternative to draw nice hands. Finally we will see that lineart can be used to inpaint bad hands, and modify an image or composition to create something new.

You will find deeper discussion about the issues above, of course the PowerPoint file in

https://powerpointopenposeeditor.wordpress.com/

items.description:
I know there is a few of stained glass lora out there, but it seems it's quite difficult to get people or animals inside the glass (tend to be a person in front of a stained glass); this lora aims to tackle this specific problem.

This lora is underbaked, it can work ranging from 0.9-2.5, depends on what other lora you put into. For example, if your lora is anime based, with line arts, you will need less of this stained glass lora, something around 0.9-1.5; vice versa.

If you want the simpler look, go for higher weight, lower weight will render your character more detailed and less glass art looking, give it some try and adjust the weight accordingly.

Finally as always, go break some eggs, have fun!

items.name: Bulgerk-dickprint
items.description:
Here's a new version of my "bulgerk" series. This time I trained on images of real people with "dickprint" or bulges which are more than just a round bulge. The original "bulgerk-soft" is here (it's a textual inversion) but I find this one gives bigger (hornier) results.

Some tips.

  • I tried to keep the training "low" to avoid overburn.

    • Some models (protogen fore example) are more "intensive" meaning that a low CFG scale of 4 or 5 is desirable

    • While some other models like virile reality might work at CFG scale of 6 for example

  • But make sure to pair this with a weight in the LoRA:

    • <lora:bulgerk-dickprint:1> should work in most cases, but it's close to "burning".

    • <lora:bulgerk-dickprint:1.2> is pretty much the max I've seen without weird stuff coming in

    • <lora:bulgerk-dickprint:0.6> will make it less unrealistic but still nice.

  • So for example, if you do

    • <lora:bulgerk-dickprint:1.2> and a CFG Scale of 4, it might work.

    • Or reverse, <lora:bulgerk-dickprint:0.5> with CFG scale of 7 might also work.

  • Prompting: I didn't bake in any prompt in the LoRA. But to get it to show up, adding bulge, or crotch bulge early in your prompt helps a lot. "A man with a crotch bulge".

  • The types of pants also seems to affect the results a lot. Jeans, chinos, cargo pants, shorts, sweatpants, etc...

After 161 models, 250 followers, 29K downloads, thanks to the 9 supporters who made it possible.

You can support me here to be able to render better models (https://ko-fi.com/djo226). Supporters can request model.

Exclusive models are also available on my Patreon.

Marv is a fictional character in the graphic novel series Sin City, created by Frank Miller. In the 2005 film adaptation and its 2014 sequel, he is played by Mickey Rourke. He first appears in The Hard Goodbye and follows with appearances in A Dame to Kill For, Just Another Saturday Night, and Silent Night. He makes a brief cameo in Blue Eyes (as featured in Lost, Lonely, and Lethal).

Marv has been well received both as a comic book character and a film character.

items.name: Lagertha from "Vikings" (2013)
items.description:
After 162 models, 250 followers, 29K downloads, thanks to the 9 supporters who made it possible.

You can support me here to be able to render better models (https://ko-fi.com/djo226). Supporters can request model.

Exclusive models are also available on my Patreon.

Vikings is a historical drama television series created and written by Michael Hirst for the History channel, a Canadian network. Filmed in Ireland, it premiered on March 3, 2013, in Canada. The series concluded on December 30, 2020

Vikings is inspired by the sagas of Ragnar Lodbrok, a Viking who is one of the best-known legendary Norse heroes and notorious as the scourge of Anglo-Saxon England and West Francia. The show portrays Ragnar as a farmer from the Kattegat who rises to fame by raiding England and eventually becomes a Scandinavian king, with the support of his family and fellow warriors.

Lagertha is the first and former wife of Ragnar Lothbrok and the former Queen of Kattegat. She is the mother of Bj√∂rn. Lagertha is an Earl and a fierce shield-maiden.

Prompt : Lagertha, realistic, natural lighting, post-processing, ultra realistic, highly detailed, very detailed, cinematic, hyper realistic, intricate scenery, sharp, photo by Annie Leibovitz, film, studio lighting, detailed skin, ultra realistic, bokeh, sharp features <lora:Lagertha:0.8>

Negative prompt: (deformed iris, deformed pupils, semi-realistic, cgi, 3d, render, sketch, cartoon, drawing, anime, mutated hands and fingers:1.4), (deformed, distorted, disfigured:1.3), poorly drawn, bad anatomy, wrong anatomy, extra limb, missing limb, floating limbs, disconnected limbs, mutation, mutated, ugly, disgusting, amputation

Steps: 90, Sampler: DPM++ 2M Karras, CFG scale: 12, Seed: -1, Face restoration: GFPGAN, Size: 768x1024, Model hash: 81086e2b3f, Model: realisticVisionV20_v20

Face restoration not activated. You can work on the negative prompt to avoid black & white.

Use Lagertha as trigger.

New process to get better result :

Set a prompt with a low weight (like <lora:Lagertha:0.4>) and the action/situation you want (even with a lower resolution like 512x768, it'll be faster and avoid duplicate). Send the result of your choice to img2img, set the weight to <lora:Lagertha:0.8>, set a higher resolution but keep proportion. Enjoy!

items.name: Centerflex
items.description:
This is a non-anime model that can handle illustrated styles in addition to photorealistic (trends to photorealistic by default).

This model contains significant softcore NSFW bias. It does not have an inherent grasp of hardcore NSFW concepts.

Prompting guide

This is a photorealistic-first model based on SD1.5. Try using only a few negative prompts/embeddings to start with, and only add more as really needed. In my experience, positive prompts like "masterpiece" aren't really necessary, but your mileage may vary. Remember that the more tokens you cram into your prompts, the more likely that certain details will be lost or ignored.

For Illustrated images

For Illustrated, cartoon, or comic/graphic novel style results, make sure "illustration" is in the positive prompt.

Recommended negative prompt for illustrated images:

3D digital, photo, blurred, grainy, low quality, artist name, signature, watermark, text, web address

You can embellish an illustration with further styles, such as the specific artist names listed in the triggers for this model, or with a hybrid illustrated style using the keyword phrase "ligne claire illustration"

For Photorealistic images

Recommended negative prompt for realistic photographs:

3D digital illustration, blurred, grainy, low quality

Artist styles

Artist styles that this model was explicitly trained to on include Roy Krenkel, Jean-Pierre Gibrat, Milo Manara, Willy Vendersteen, Francois Schuiten, Edgar P Jacobs, Herge, Jacques Tardi, and Moebius.

To invoke a specific artist styles, simply add "by Artist Name" to the positive prompt, e.g., "illustration of a woman on a tropical beach, by Roy Krenkel"

Artist names can have a very strong impact; try them with weak weights, e.g. "(by Roy Krenkel:0.1)" or "(by Jean-Pierre Gibrat:0.1)" and see how a dash of their style influences the composition and color scheme.

Ligne claire

This model contains a general activation keyword phrase to evoke a certain hybrid comic book style and composition. This phrase is "ligne claire" meaning "clear line" after the Franco-Belgian comic book tradition.

For example: "A ligne claire illustration of a female science fiction bounty hunter."

Background/history

A funny thing happened when I was training my photorealistic Centerfold Blend. I found that when I incorporated illustrated images in the training data (properly tagged, of course) the model produced better photorealistic images.

Centerflex is an extension of Centerfold Blend, with a great deal more non-photographic training data. It is intended to be more flexible than Centerfold (hence the name Center+Flex), especially regarding illustrated styles. It was trained with a variety of artist styles in addition to high quality photographs of people.
